In article <246ea4$123@charm.magnus.acs.ohio-state.edu>
jebright@magnus.acs.ohio-state.edu (James R Ebright) writes:
 
>We once asked the IBM folks who developed DES why the key was only 56 bits
>and if the NSA had anything to do with the length.  They replied 56 bits
>was all they could get on the chip they developed (remember, this was
>before 8080s even!) and the NSA had nothing to do with the length.
 
   Hmmm.  Seems hard to imagine that you'd radically downsize your key to
fit the chip you were working on.  Especially with the collection of first-
rate cryptographers involved in designing the system.  Surely this isn't
the real answer!
 
